48
00:02:03,920 --> 00:02:08,319
Well, if they say, I'm sorry, someone is sitting here, that means that maybe they're waiting for a friend.

49
00:02:08,319 --> 00:02:09,759
And then, no, you can't sit there.

50
00:02:09,759 --> 00:02:16,639
But if they say, sure, like in the dialogue, feel free, then you're really basically able to sit down, no problem.

51
00:02:17,419 --> 00:02:20,439
Right, so the stranger answers by saying, no, please feel free.

52
00:02:20,520 --> 00:02:24,000
So he says, no, the seat is not taken, please feel free.

53
00:02:24,120 --> 00:02:25,379
What does he mean by this?

54
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:29,919
Okay, feel free is a very unusual phrase in English, but one that you're going to hear a lot.

55
00:02:30,439 --> 00:02:32,800
It basically means, do what you want to do.

56
00:02:33,219 --> 00:02:33,360
Okay.

57
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:36,479
Okay, so if I want to sit down, I say, is this seat taken?

58
00:02:36,479 --> 00:02:40,120
If you say, feel free, Marco, that means, feel free to sit down.

59
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:48,919
Okay, so we can complete the sentence by saying, no, please feel free to sit down, but it's kind of stating the obvious.

60
00:02:48,960 --> 00:02:51,259
You're saying, basically, feel free to do what you want.

61
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:52,900
That's right, but you could use it in other ways.

62
00:02:52,939 --> 00:02:56,520
For example, hey, Marco, are you using this pen right here?

63
00:02:56,699 --> 00:02:57,759
No, no, feel free.

64
00:02:58,060 --> 00:03:00,180
That means, feel free to use my pen.

65
00:03:00,460 --> 00:03:01,539
Okay, very good.

66
00:03:02,780 --> 00:03:09,120
So then they started talking about what they do, where they work, and Michelle said, yes, I work in Shanghai.

67
00:03:09,539 --> 00:03:10,800
How about you?

68
00:03:11,340 --> 00:03:12,159
Oh, how about you?

69
00:03:12,319 --> 00:03:14,840
Now, this is a really important construction.

70
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:18,740
This is a really important phrase in English, and I think a lot of people make mistakes with this.

71
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:23,680
So how about you means, do you work in Shanghai?

72
00:03:23,879 --> 00:03:25,800
I just said, I work in Shanghai, but how about you?

73
00:03:25,919 --> 00:03:26,360
Do you?

74
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:27,840
Right, exactly.

75
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:29,379
So that's saying, and you?

76
00:03:29,879 --> 00:03:30,719
Do you work here?

77
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:31,539
Or, and you?

78
00:03:31,719 --> 00:03:32,419
What do you do?

79
00:03:32,740 --> 00:03:33,340
How about you?

80
00:03:33,740 --> 00:03:45,599
Now, the common mistake with how about you, or using the construction how about, is that, for some reason, some people seem to think that it means, how is it?

81
00:03:46,139 --> 00:03:49,879
So, for example, if someone says, how about your weekend?

82
00:03:51,020 --> 00:03:51,780
That's wrong.

83
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:52,979
No, we don't say that.

84
00:03:53,139 --> 00:03:54,379
How was your weekend?

85
00:03:54,379 --> 00:03:59,120
But in this case, how about you always follows a statement.

86
00:03:59,759 --> 00:04:02,539
Okay, so yes, I do live in Shanghai, how about you?

87
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:04,300
That means, do you live in Shanghai?

88
00:04:04,860 --> 00:04:09,099
If I say, I would like to eat a hamburger and french fries, how about you?

89
00:04:09,199 --> 00:04:09,719
How about you?

90
00:04:09,919 --> 00:04:10,860
What would you like to eat?

91
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:11,419
Exactly.

92
00:04:11,759 --> 00:04:14,159
So remember, that's the way that you use how about.

93
00:04:14,580 --> 00:04:20,699
Never say, how about your weekend, or how about your vacation, when you want to ask, how was it?

94
00:04:20,779 --> 00:04:21,540
Don't say that.

95
00:04:21,540 --> 00:04:28,199
No, basically this is a way to reply to someone when they're telling you about their experience, you want to talk about yours.

96
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:29,180
That's right.

